INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('uk-', 'uk-', 'to understand, find out, hear', '<b>uk-</b> ‘to understand (something Acc.); hence in some modern languages ‘to find out; to hear’. Survives in NE, SE, NC.; an early l.-w. in Mong. as <b>uka-</b> (Haenisch 160, Kow. 257). In some forms, esp. in unvocalized texts, liable to be confused with <b>okı:-</b>. In the early period often in the Hend. <b>bil- uk-</b>. <b>Türkü</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>bilmetin ukmatın</b> ‘because (we) do not know or understand’ Chuas. 132: <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <i>M I</i> 18, 4 (i) (<b>aḏır-</b>): Bud. <b>uk-</b> is common, e.g. <b>tétrü ukar</b> ‘he completely understands’ U II 7, 6; o.o. do. 8, 22; 9, 12; 11, 11; <i>TT</i> <i>V</i> 26, 96; <i>VIII</i> O.1; PP 68, 5—<b>bil- uk-</b> U III 35. 22; <i>TT</i> <i>IV</i> 4, 11; <i>VI</i> 331: Civ. <b>iş bolmışın uka yarlıkap</b> ‘deigning to understand what has occurred’ USp. 88, 11: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>er i:şın ukdı:</b> <i>ḍālika''l-racul faṭana amrahu</i> ‘that man understood his business’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 168 (<b>uka:r</b>, <b>ukma:k</b>); three o.o.: <i>KB</i> <b>uk-</b> ‘to understand’ is common, esp. for ‘to understand what has been said’, e.g. <b>él(l)ig aydı uktum</b> ‘the king said “I understand”’ 714; o.o. 155, 282, 657, 660, 680, etc.: xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>eşit uk munı</b> ‘hear and understand this’ 62; a.o.o.: <i>Tef.</i> <b>uk-</b> ditto 324: xıv <i>Muh.</i> <i>''arafa wa ''alima</i> ‘to know’ <b>u:k-</b> Rif. 112: <b>Xwar.</b> xııı(?) <b>ukğuluk tüzün bir er</b> ‘an understanding and gentle man’ <i>Oğ.</i> 314 (reading doubtful): xıv <b>uk-</b> ‘to understand’ <i>Qutb</i> 117 (<b>ok-</b>); 199 (<b>uk-</b>): <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>uk-</b> <i>fahima</i> ‘to understand’ <i>İd.</i> 17.', 'Basic', '[]', 77, 'MON. V. AG-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağı:', 'ağı:', 'treasure, silk brocade', '<b>ağı:</b> from xı onwards consistently translated ‘silk brocade’ and the like; earlier contexts suggest the meaning ‘treasure’, and cf. <b>ağı:çı:</b>, <b>ağı:lık</b>; ‘silk brocade’, as the main component of early Turkish treasures, may, however, have been the original meaning. N.o.a.b. The word <b>ağ/ağı</b> prob. used only in such phr. as <b>ağı kurdu</b> ‘caterpillar’ noted in <b>Osm.</b> xvı TTS II 9 and surviving in xx Anat. SDD 74, 76, 78, 131, 1602 prob. has nothing to do with ‘silk’ (worm); it seems to be a Sec. f. of <b>ağu:</b>. Cf. <b>barçın</b>. <b>Türkü</b> vııı <b>ağı:</b> occurs 5 times in I S 5-7, II N 4-5, and several times elsewhere in the context of gifts given by the Chinese to the Turks; in I S 5, II N 4 it summarizes a list of such gifts ‘gold, silver’, and two words prob. meaning silken fabrics of some kind, so prob. means ‘treasure’; in a list of booty in T 48 <b>sarığ altu:n ürüŋ kümüş kız koḏuz egri: teve: ağı:</b> ‘yellow gold, white silver, girls, femmes soles, humped camels’ . . . it looks more like ‘brocade’; in other occurrences it could be either, but ‘treasure’ is more probable: vııı ff. Man. <b>[gap katı]ğlanmaz ınçıp ağı bulur; yéme [ne t]örlüg ağı barım elgiŋerü kelser esirgenü kısğanu tutmaz kizlemez</b> ‘he makes no efforts but still acquires treasures; and whatever treasures and property come into his hands he does not retain and hide them in miserliness and greed’ M III 21, 1-4 (i) (here, esp. in the Hend., ‘treasure’ must be the meaning): <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>ağı barım</b> <i>M I</i> 15, 4-5; M III 11, 20; 13, 6-7 (i): Bud. <b>ağı barım</b> U II 76, 2; PP 7, 6 and 9; 9, 2; <i>TT</i> <i>VI</i> 101, 233, 266; Tiş. 19a. 4: Civ. <b>ağı barım</b> <i>TT</i> <i>VII</i> 34, 3: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağır</b> <i>al-dībāc</i> ‘silk brocade’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 89; (do not rejoice) <b>altun kümüş bulnupan ağı: tava:r</b> <i>iḍā wacadta . . . fiḍḍa wa ḍahab wa dībāc</i> ‘if you acquire gold and silver and silk brocade’ <i>II</i> 153, 8 (but <b>tava:r</b> (untranslated) suggests ‘treasure’ would be better): <i>KB</i> <b>ağı çuz ağır boldı</b> ‘silk brocades (Hend.) are valuable’ 902; <b>açtı ağı kaznakı</b> ‘he opened his treasury’ (and distributed many things to the poor) 1034; <b>çığayka üledi kümüş ham ağı</b> ‘he distributed silver and treasure (or silk brocade?) to the poor’ 1564; <b>ağı çuz</b> 1426, 4773, 5367: xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>altun kümüş ağu</b> (sic) <b>barçın</b> (‘brocade’) 39: xıv <i>Muh.</i>(?) <i>al-ṯawbu''l-ibrīsamī</i> ‘silken clothing’ <b>ağı:</b> Rif. 167 (only): <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>ağı:</b> ‘a kind of silk’ (<i>al-ḥarīr</i>) <i>İd.</i> 17: <b>Osm.</b> xıv (when a boy grows up he must marry, and you must give him) <b>ağı atlas at katır</b> ‘brocade, damask, a horse, and a mule’ TTS I 7; <b>bağışladı altun kızıl u ağı</b> ‘he gave red gold and brocade’ TTS II 9.', 'Basic', '[]', 78, 'DIS. AĞA');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('akı:', 'akı:', 'generous, openhanded', '<b>akı:</b> ‘generous, openhanded’. <i>TT</i> <i>VI</i> 57, note 4 suggests that this is a Dev. N. in -ı: fr. <b>ak-</b>, which is possible but improbable. Survives only(?) in NE Bar. <b>ağu:</b> R I 172; SW <b>Osm.</b> <b>axı</b> ‘a member of a charitable religious order’. It has been suggested that the latter is der. fr. <i>Ar. ax</i> ‘brother’, but this is improbable, see <b>akı:lık</b>. See Doerfer <i>II</i> 435. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>buşı bérgeli akı tınlığlar az</b> ‘generous people who gives alms are scarce’ <i>TT</i> <i>VI</i> 4: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>akı:</b> <i>al-cawād</i> ‘generous’; hence ‘a ripe walnut’ (<i>al-cawzu''l-farīk</i>) is called <b>akı: yağa:k</b> ‘that is a generous walnut’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 90 (presumably because it is split open like a hand): <i>KB</i> <b>akı keŋ elig</b> ‘generous and openhanded’ 43, 55; o.o. 104, 257, 948, etc.: xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>axī</b> ‘generous’, always so spelt in Ar. script is common: <b>Xwar.</b> xıv <b>akı</b> ‘generous’ <i>Qutb</i> 10: <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>al-karīm</i> ‘generous’ <b>akı:</b> (opposite to ‘mean’ <b>çokma:r(?)</b>) <i>Hou.</i> 26, 2: xıv <b>ağı:</b> ditto <i>İd.</i> 17: <b>Osm.</b> xıv <b>axī</b> (used by wife to husband); xvı (used by father to son) TTS II 7.', 'Basic', '[]', 78, 'DIS. AGA');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('1 ağu:', '1 ağu:', 'poison', '<b>1 ağu:</b> ‘poison’. S.i.a.m.l.g., often contracted to <b>o:</b>, <b>u:</b>, etc.; see <b>ağı:</b>. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man.-A <b>sizlerde almış ağu</b> ‘the poison received from you’ <i>M I</i> 19, 15-16; 20, 1 (<b>at-</b>): Man. <b>ağusı küçedip</b> ‘the poison in him taking strong hold of him’ (or ‘making him violent’?) <i>TT</i> <i>II</i> 16, 13: Bud. (there is a poisonous snake) <b>ağu tını</b> ‘his poisonous breath’ PP 38, 4: Civ. <b>ağu</b> ‘poison’ H II 6, 9; 30, 170: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağu:</b> <i>al-samm</i> ‘poison’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 89; a.o. <i>III</i> 339, 21: <i>KB</i> <b>ağu kıldı</b> ‘it has poisoned’ (my food) 370; (begs when they are angry) <b>bolur öt ağu</b> ‘are gall and poison’ 779 (better reading than <b>ot</b> ‘fire’?); <b>ağu boldı</b> ‘he is poisoned’ 4655; a.o. 3913 (<b>1 açığ</b>): xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>içi pur ağu</b> ‘its inside is full of poison’ 214; <i>Tef.</i> <b>ağu</b> ‘poison’ 39: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>ağu</b> <i>zahr</i> ‘poison’ <i>San.</i> 44r. 8 (quotn.): <b>Xwar.</b> xıv <b>ağu</b> ‘poison’ <i>Qutb</i> 5; <i>Nahc.</i> 33, 11: <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>al-murr</i> ‘bitterness’ . . . also <b>ağu:</b> <i>al-samm</i> so used by analogy because of its bitterness <i>Hou.</i> 27, 10: xıv <b>ağu:</b> <i>al-samm</i> <i>İd.</i> 17; <b>awu:</b> ditto, do. 26; ditto <b>ağu:</b> <i>Bul.</i> 11, 6: xv <i>samm</i> <b>awu</b> in <b>Tkm.</b> <b>ağu</b> <i>Tuh.</i> 19b. 2.', 'Basic', '[]', 78, 'DIS. AĞA');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('2 ağu:', '2 ağu:', NULL, '<b>2 ağu:</b> in <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>[gap] gözlügler köplüg ağu teg butluğlar</b> ‘having . . . eyes, and legs like abundant . . .’ <i>TT</i> <i>IX</i> 85 can hardly mean ‘poison’, but its actual meaning and etymology are obscure.', 'Basic', '[]', 78, 'DIS. AĞA');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('1 okı:-', '1 okı:-', 'call out, summon, recite, read', '<b>1 okı:-</b> originally ‘to call out aloud’, hence ‘to summon (someone Acc.)’, ‘to recite or read aloud’, and finally simply ‘to read’ which is the normal modern meaning. S.i.a.m.l.g. except NE. (<b>Türkü</b> vııı <b>okığlı: kelti:</b> has been read after a gap in <i>II</i> E 28, but hardly fits the context, the true reading is probably something like <b>[uts]u:kığlı: kelti:</b>): <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>bu emig iki kata okıyu tegintim</b> ‘I have ventured to recite this spell(?) three times’ <i>M I</i> 29, 13-15; o.o. do. 30, 17, 26, 6 and 7; <b>okıyurlar</b> ‘they call on’ (the Wind God) Wind. 249, 18: Bud. <b>toyu:nla:rığ okıp</b> ‘summoning the monks’ <i>TT</i> <i>VIII</i> H.1; <b>inisin okıyu</b> ‘calling for his younger brother’ PP 58, 3; <b>okumak törüsin</b> ‘the ceremony of invoking’ (gods, demons, etc.) <i>TT</i> <i>V</i> 10, 114; o.o. USp. 103, 13; Suv. 447, 16, etc.: xıv <i>Chin.-Uyğ. Dict.</i> ‘read the book’ <b>bitig okı</b> R I 1008; Ligeti 186: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol meni: okı:dı:</b> <i>da''ānī</i> ‘he summoned me’; and one says <b>er bitig okı:dı:</b> ‘the man read (<i>qara''a</i>) the book’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>III</i> 254 (<b>okı:r</b>, <b>okı:ma:k</b>); a.o. 333, 5 (<b>sékrit-</b>): <i>KB</i> <b>silig kız okır teg köŋül bérmişin</b> ‘as a pure maiden calls the man to whom she has given her heart’ 75; (if a generous man dies) <b>atı tirig tép okı</b> ‘call out that his name lives’ 257; <b>bu kün kim okısa</b> ‘whoever reads (the book) today’ 259; o.o. 319, 719, 3535: xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>okığlı kişi</b> ‘the man who reads (my book)’ 44; 3 o.o.: <i>Tef.</i> <b>okı-</b> ‘to call out; to read’ 235: xıv <i>Muh.</i>(?) <i>qara''a</i> <b>okı-</b> Rif. 114 (only); <i>al-qirā''a</i> <b>o:kı:mak</b> 124: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>oku-</b> <i>xwāndan</i> ‘to recite, invoke, read’ <i>San.</i> 77r. 12 (quotns.): <b>Xwar.</b> xııı <b>oku-</b> ‘to call out’ <i>''Ali</i> 29: xıv <b>okı-/oku-</b> ‘to call out, recite’ <i>Qutb</i> 118; <i>MN</i> 50, etc.: <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>qara''a</i> <b>okı:-</b> <i>Hou.</i> 33, 13: xıv <b>okı:-</b> <i>qara''a</i>, and in Kıpçak (sic) <b>oğu:-</b> <i>İd.</i> 17; <i>qara''a</i> <b>oku-</b> <i>Bul.</i> 72r.: xv ditto <i>Kav.</i> 9, 14 a.o.o.; <i>Tuh.</i> 30a. 2 a.o.o.: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>okı-(xıv only) /oku-</b> ‘to call, summon’, etc.; c.i.a.p. TTS I 538; TTS II 723; TTS III 537; TTS IV 603.', 'Basic', '[]', 79, 'DIS. V. AGA-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('2 okı:-', '2 okı:-', 'belch, vomit', 'PU <b>2 okı:-</b> ‘to belch, vomit’. Survives in NE Tel. <b>okı-</b> R I 994; Tuv. <b>oğu-</b> and SW xx Anat. ögü- SDD 1104. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>er okı:dı:</b> ‘the man vomited’ (<i>taqayya''a</i>); <i>wa hāḍā rikkatu''l-kāf</i> (see Preliminary note) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>III</i> 254 (<b>okı:r</b>, <b>okı:ma:k</b>); <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>öki-</b> (so spelt; v.l. <b>öğü-</b>, so spelt) <i>taqayya''a</i> <i>İd.</i> 18.', 'Basic', '[]', 79, 'DIS. V. AGA-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağuc', 'ağuc', NULL, 'S <b>ağuc</b> See <b>ağuz</b>.', 'Basic', '[]', 79, 'DIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ığaç', 'ığaç', 'tree, wood, piece of wood, parasang', '<b>ığaç</b> (<b>ığa:ç</b>) originally ‘tree’, in <b>Uyğ.</b> esp. in the phr. <b>ı: ığaç</b> ‘shrubs and trees’; hence ‘wood (generally), a piece of wood’. At least fr. xı onwards the word was also used for a large unit of linear measurement, conventionally a parasang of 4 or 5 miles, perhaps originally a time-distance measure like ‘an hour’s journey’; it is hard to see any semantic connection between the two meanings. The phonetic history, too, like that of <b>ığla:-</b>, q.v., is complicated. Before xı the form was consistently <b>ığaç</b> but in <b>Xak.</b> became <b>yığaç</b> with a prosthetic y-, which survives only in SC <b>Uzb. yoğoç</b> ‘wood’ (for ‘tree’ <i>Persian daraxt</i> is used) and <b>Çuv.</b>, <b>yavāş/yivăç</b> (<b>yavāş</b>, <b>yıvāşy</b>) Ash. <i>IV</i> 161, 297. In all other modern language groups the form is <b>ağaç</b>, with variations of the -ç in NE, NC. <b>Türkü</b> vııı <b>çıntan ığaç kelürüp</b> ‘bringing logs of sandal-wood’ <i>II</i> S 11; <b>at yete: yadağın ığaç tutunu: ağtu:rtım</b> ‘I made the men climb on foot leading their horses and holding on to the trees’ T 25: vııı ff. Man.; <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. <b>çıntan ığaç üze: olu:ru:pan</b> ‘sitting on a sandal-wood tree’ IrkB 4; o.o. meaning ‘tree’ do. 14, 56: Man. <b>béş törlüg ot ığaç</b> ‘the five kinds of vegetables and trees’ Chuas. 59, 317; <b>1 ığaç</b> M <i>III</i> 14, 12 (i): <b>Uyğ.</b> Man.-A (just as fire) <b>ıgaçda ünüp ığaçağ örteyür</b> ‘arises from wood and burns wood’ <i>M I</i> 7, 2; <b>1 ığaç</b> do. 8, 19; 13, 8: Man. <b>1 ığaç</b> M <i>II</i> 12, 5: Bud. <b>1 ığaç</b> Suv. 621, 5; <b>ığaç</b> ‘drum-stick’ Suv. 375, 7; <b>uzun sıruk ığaç başında</b> ‘on the top of a long pole’ USp. 104, 12-13; o.o. <i>TT</i> <i>VI</i> 323; Pfahl. 8, 10: Civ. <b>küzki ığaç yaŋkusı</b> ‘the rustle of trees in autumn’ <i>TT</i> <i>I</i> 134; <b>ığaç</b> ‘wood’ as one of the five elements, and metaph. for the planet Jupiter <i>TT</i> <i>VII</i> 1, 32, and 79 (spelt <b>yığaç</b>); 10, 6; <b>kara kaç ığaç kasıkın</b> ‘the bark of a black <b>kaç</b> tree’ H <i>I</i> 26: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>yığaç</b> <i>al-xaşab</i> ‘wood’; <b>yığaç</b> <i>ḍakaru''l-racul</i> ‘a man’s penis’; <b>yığaç</b> <i>ul-farsax mina''l-arḍ</i> ‘a parasang of ground’; hence one says <b>bi:r yığaç yé:r</b> ‘one parasang of ground’; <b>yığaç</b> <i>al-şacar</i> ‘a tree’; hence one says <b>üzüm yığaçı:</b> <i>şacaru''l-inab</i> ‘a vine’ and <b>yağa:k yığa:çı:</b> <i>şacaru''l-cawz</i> ‘a nut tree’; <b>yığa:ç</b> with -a:- is the better spelling (<i>acwad</i>) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>III</i> 8; <b>yığa:ç</b> alternative form (<i>luğa</i>) of <b>yığaç</b> <i>III</i> 28; and nearly 120 o.o.: <i>KB</i> (green covers) <b>kurımış yığaçlar</b> ‘the dry trees’ 70; <b>yemişsiz yığaç</b> ‘a tree without fruit’ 2455: xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>yémīşsiz yığaç</b> 323, 324; <i>Tef.</i> <b>ağaç/yağaç/yığaç</b> (1) ‘tree’; (2) ‘beam’; (3) ‘parasang’ 37, 132, 133: xıv <i>Muh.</i>(?) <i>naccār</i> ‘carpenter’ <b>ığa:ç</b> (unvocalized) <b>yoncı:</b> Rif. 158 (only); <i>al-aṣā</i> ‘a stick, staff’ <b>ığa:ç</b> 173; <i>al-farsax</i> <b>ığa:ç</b> 178: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>yığaç</b> if a man stands at a particular place and two men stand one on each side of him so that they can hear him when he shouts, they call three times this distance (<b>üç martaba bu miqdārın</b>) <b>yığaç</b> (quotns.); and also <i>bannā arşūn</i> . . . <i>karı ma''nāsına</i> ‘a builder’s cubit’ (about 30 inches) (quotn.) <i>Vel.</i> 413 (the latter is an error, the verse describes 12,000 <b>kari</b> as a <b>yığaç</b>); <b>yığaç</b> (1) <i>çūb</i> ‘wood’; (2) <i>farsang</i> ‘parasang’ <i>San.</i> 350v. 3 (quotns.): <b>Xwar.</b> xııı <b>yığaç</b> ‘tree’ <i>''Ali</i> 49: xııı(?) <b>ığaç</b> (once spelt <b>yığaç</b>) ‘tree’ is common <i>Oğ.</i>: xıv <b>agaç/yığaç</b> ‘tree, parasang’ <i>Qutb</i> 4, 90; <i>Nahc.</i> 24, 2; 186, 13: <b>Kom.</b> xıv <b>ağaç</b> ‘tree; wood, beam, column, (saddle)-tree’ <i>CCI</i>, <i>CCG</i>; <i>Gr.</i> 28 (quotns.): <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>al-şacara wa''l-xaşab wa''l-''aṣā</i> <b>ağa:ç</b> <i>Hou.</i> 7, 10: xıv <b>ağaç</b> <i>al-''aṣā wa''l-şacar</i>; one says <b>alma: ağaçı:</b> ‘apple tree’ <i>İd.</i> 17: xv <i>al-''aṣā</i> <b>ağaş</b> <i>Kav.</i> 31, 7; 39, 8: <i>al-şacar</i> <b>ağaş</b>: as in <b>alma: ağa:şı:</b>, and <b>ağa:ş</b> <i>al-xaşab</i> do. 59, 3; <i>carīd</i> ‘a defoliated palm-branch’ <b>ağaş</b> <i>Tuh.</i> 11b. 10; <i>xaşab</i> ditto 14b. 1; <i>''aṣā</i> ditto 25b. 3: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>ağaç</b> ‘tree; stick, blow from a stick’ and twice (xıv and xvı) ‘parasang’; c.i.a.p. TTS <i>I</i> 5; <i>II</i> 7; <i>III</i> 4-5; <i>IV</i> 5.', 'Basic', '["ığa:ç"]', 79, 'DIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okçı:', 'okçı:', 'arrow-maker, archer', 'D <b>okçı:</b> N.Ag. fr. <b>1 ok</b>; ‘arrow-maker; archer’. Survives only(?) in SW <b>Osm. Xak.</b> xı <b>okçı:</b> <i>al-nabbāl</i> ‘arrow-maker’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>II</i> 199, 3 (<b>köndger-</b>); n.m.e.: <i>KB</i> <b>yadağ okçı tuşrup sen öŋdün yügür</b> ‘concentrate your infantry bowmen, and ride out in front yourself’ 2370 (or read <b>tüçrüp</b> ‘make your bowmen dismount’); (in a list of craftsmen) <b>okçı:</b> ‘arrow-maker’ 4458: xıv <i>Muh.</i>(?) <i>naşşābi</i> ‘arrow-maker’ <b>o:kçı:</b> Rif. 157 (only): <b>Xwar.</b> xıv <b>okçı</b> ‘archer’ <i>Qutb</i> 117: <b>Kom.</b> xıv arrow-maker’ <b>oxçı</b> <i>CCI</i>; <i>Gr.</i>: <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>al-naşşābī</i> <b>okçı:</b>; and also <i>al-rāmī bi''l-nuşşāb</i> ‘archer’ <i>Hou.</i> 24, 7.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'DIS. AGC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağı:çı:', 'ağı:çı:', 'treasurer', 'D <b>ağı:çı:</b> N.Ag. fr. <b>ağı:</b>; an official title the exact significance of which is discussed by Caferoğlu in TM <i>IV</i> 20; ‘treasurer’ or the like. N.o.a.b. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>ağıçı uluğı</b> ‘the chief treasurer’ PP 7, 7; <b>ağıçı</b> do. 9, 7 and 8; 10, 8: Civ. <b>tsaŋçı ağıçılar almazun</b> ‘let the granary-keepers and treasurers not take’ USp. 88, 40; <b>Koço balık ağıçı</b> ‘the town treasurer of Koço’ do. 115, 19: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağı:çı:</b> <i>xāzinu''l-dībāc</i> ‘the keeper of the silk brocades’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 136; (after <b>ağı:</b>) hence <i>al-xāzin</i> is called <b>ağı:çı:</b> because he keeps it (<i>li-ḥifẓihi iyyāhu</i>) <i>I</i> 89, 20: <i>KB</i> (in a list of officials) <b>ağıçı</b> 2494; <b>bitig bilse sakış ağıçı bolur</b> ‘if (a young man) can read and keep accounts, he becomes a treasurer’ 4048.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ığaççı:', 'ığaççı:', 'carpenter, wood-worker', 'D <b>ığaççı:</b> N.Ag. fr. <b>ığaç</b>; ‘carpenter, woodworker’, etc. Survives in NE Tuv. <b>ıyaşçı</b> NC <b>Kır. jığaççı</b>; <b>Kzx. ağaşşı</b>. <b>Uyğ.</b> xııı ff. Bud. <i>Sanskrit vardhakīnaḥ</i> ‘carpenters’ <b>ığaç-cıla:r</b> (sic) <i>TT</i> <i>VIII</i> A.12; <b>ığaççı</b> Pfahl. 24, 3 and 4: (<b>Xak.</b>) xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>yağaççı/yığaççı</b> ‘carpenter’ 132, 156.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okı:çı:', 'okı:çı:', 'preacher, reader', 'D <b>okı:çı:</b> N.Ag. fr. <b>okı:-</b>. S.i.s.m.l. usually as <b>okuçı</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <i>KB</i> <b>okıçı ol erdi bayattın saŋa</b> ‘he was a preacher (sent) from God to you’ 36: <b>Kıp.</b> xv (in grammatical examples) <b>okuçı/okuçu</b> not translated but alternating with <b>yazuçı</b> so presumably ‘reader’ <i>Tuh.</i> 80a. 6 and 7; b. 4.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. AGC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('*ığaçlık', '*ığaçlık', 'copse, plantation, wood-store', 'D <b>*ığaçlık</b> A.N. (Conc. N.) fr. <b>ığaç</b>. S.i.s.m.l. as <b>ağaçlık</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>yığaçlık</b> <i>al-maşcara</i> ‘copse, plantation’; also <i>dāru''l-xaşab</i> ‘a wood-store’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>III</i> 51.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağujluğ', 'ağujluğ', 'who owns biestings', 'D <b>ağujluğ</b> Hap. leg.; P.N./A. fr. <b>ağuj/ağuz</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağujluğ</b> ‘(a man) who owns biestings’ (<i>libā''</i>) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 146.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. AĞC');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('*ığaçlan-', '*ığaçlan-', 'be covered with trees', 'D <b>*ığaçlan-</b> Refl. Den. V. fr. <b>ığaç</b>. S.i.s.m.l., usually as <b>ağaçlan-</b>; the basic form <b>*ığaçla:-</b>also survives with a rather wider range of meanings. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>yé:r yığaçlandı:</b> <i>aşcarati''l-arḍ</i> ‘the ground was covered with trees’, that is there were many trees on it <i>Kaş.</i> <i>III</i> 113 (<b>yığaçlanu:r</b>, <b>yığaçlanma:k</b>): <b>Osm.</b> xv <b>ağaçlan-</b> ‘to be beaten with a stick’ TTS <i>II</i> 7.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'TRIS. V. AĞC-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('uğut', 'uğut', 'yeast', '<b>uğut</b> ‘yeast’. Survives in NE Şor R <i>I</i> 1619: SE <b>Türki</b> Shaw 24; NC <b>Kır.</b>; and, with a slightly different meaning, in SW xx Anat. <b>uğut</b>, <b>uhut</b>, <b>uğunt</b> SDD 1415. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>uğut</b> a word for ‘yeast’ (<i>xamīr</i>) used in making beer (<i>al-mizz</i>). It is various vegetable drugs (<i>adwiya</i>) which are collected and mixed with (specially) grown barley; the whole is then kneaded, cut into pieces the size of a nut and dried. Then wheat and barley are boiled, and the yeast is broken up, and an amount the size of a nut is sprinkled on each (lot of) wheat. The boiled wheat is then folded over and put on a clean thing (<i>şay''</i>) to ferment for three days. Then it is picked up and put in a jar and left to ferment in it for (another) ten days. Then water is put on it and later strained. This is ‘wheat wine’ (<i>şarābu''l-ḥinṭa</i>) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 50.', 'Basic', '[]', 80, 'DIS. AĞD');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağduk', 'ağduk', 'fault, defect, useless, bad, stranger, foreigner', 'D <b>ağduk</b> prob., as <i>Kaş.</i> suggests, N./A. S. fr. <b>2 a:ğ-</b>, although there is little semantic connection. Survives only(?) in SW xx Anat. <b>ağdık</b> ‘fault, defect; useless, bad; excessively heavy’ SDD 73, unless NE Şor <b>adık</b> ‘weak-minded, confused’ is also a survival. The original meaning seems to have been ‘stranger, foreigner’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man.-A <b>maŋa ağduk karı bétkeçi</b> ‘to me, the foreign old scribe’ <i>M I</i> 28, 19; same phr. (damaged) do. 21, title; <b>men ağduk bét[keçi]</b> M <i>III</i> 43, 12-13 (v. le Coq, perhaps rightly, took this to be a Proper Name): <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağduk kişi:</b> <i>al-raculu''l-daxīlu''llaḍī lā yu''raf man huwa</i> ‘a stranger whose identity is unknown’; <b>adğuk</b> alternative metathesized form <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 99; <b>aḏuk ne:ŋ</b> <i>al-şay''u''l-machūl</i> ‘an unknown thing’; its origin is <b>ağduk</b> meaning <i>mutağayyir mutanakkir</i> ‘altered, changed’, derived from the expression <b>anıŋ meŋzi: ağdı:</b> <i>tağayyara lawnuhu</i> ‘his colour changed’, with the -ğ-eliminated as an abbreviation <i>I</i> 65: <b>Osm.</b> xıv to xvı <b>ağduk</b> ‘changed; damaged, imperfect; inopportune’ in several texts TTS <i>I</i> 6; <i>II</i> 8; <i>III</i> 5; <i>IV</i> 6.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'DIS. AĞD');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oktam', 'oktam', 'space the length of a bowshot', 'D <b>oktam</b> Hap. leg.; N.S.A. fr. <b>okta:-</b>. Cf. <b>atım</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>bir oktam yé:r</b> <i>qadar ramya mina''l-arḍ</i> ‘a space the length of a bowshot’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 107.', 'D', '[]', 80, 'DIS. AGD');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağıt-', 'ağıt-', 'make climb, make rise', 'D <b>ağıt-</b> Caus. f. of <b>1 a:ğ-</b>. N.o.a.b. Cf. <b>ağtur-</b>. <b>Türkü</b> vııı Kül Tégin <b>ağıtıp</b> ‘Kül Tégin roused (that part of) their army which had escaped’ <i>I</i> N 7; parallel passage <i>II</i> E 30-1; (his horse fell) <b>yana: ağıtıp</b> ‘making it get up again’ <i>I</i> x. 19 (sic on stone, not <b>ağilip</b> as in printed text): vııı ff. Man. <b>billgimizni köŋülümüzni bu tört törlüg teŋrilerde ağıtdımız erser</b> ‘if we have exalted our knowledge and minds above these four kinds of gods’ Chuas. 184-7: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol anı: ta:ğka: ağıttı:</b> ‘he made him climb (<i>aṣ''adahu</i>) the mountain (etc.)’; and one says <b>teŋri: bulıt ağıttı:</b> ‘God made a cloud rise’ (<i>anşa''a . . . saḥāba</i>) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 212 (<b>ağıtur</b>, <b>ağıtma:k</b>); <b>bu: keyik ol ı:tığ ta:ğka: ağıtğa:n</b> ‘this wild game is constantly making the dog climb (<i>yuṣa''''id</i>) the mountain’ <i>I</i> 155: <i>KB</i> (Why do you grieve? Why these lamentations? God’s summons has come.) <b>sığıtnı ağıt</b> ‘Away with lamentations’ 1233 (an inappropriate use of the word, but perhaps the only rhyme for <b>sığıt</b>).', 'D', '[]', 80, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('akıt-', 'akıt-', 'make flow, send out to raid', 'D <b>akıt-</b> Caus. f. of <b>ak-</b>; ‘to make (liquid, etc.) flow; to send out (a party, etc.) to raid’. s.i.a.m.l.g., except SC, as <b>akıt-</b>/<b>ağıt-</b> in both meanings. Cf. <b>aktur-</b>. <b>Türkü</b> vııı Kül Tégin <b>beg başlayu: akıt(t)ımız</b> ‘we sent out a raiding party under the command of Kül Tégin and the begs’ <i>I</i> N 8 (hitherto misread); <b>tün akıtdımız</b> ‘we sent out a raiding party by night’ T 35: <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>buyanlığ taluy ögüz akıtıp</b> ‘causing an ocean of virtues to flow’ <i>TT III</i> 163: Bud. <b>kan ögüz akıtar</b> (sic) ‘they cause rivers of blood to flow’ PP 3, 4; a.o. <i>TT VI</i> 136 (<b>ak-</b>). <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>teŋri: akın akıttı:</b> ‘God made the stream flow’ (<i>asāla''l-sayl</i>); and one says <b>ol su:v akıttı:</b> ‘he poured out (<i>acrā</i>) the water’; and one says <b>beg akınçı: akıttı:</b> ‘the beg sent a raiding party (<i>ba''aṯa . . . sarīya</i>) against the enemy’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 212 (<b>akıtur</b>, <b>akıtma:k</b>); <b>bu: ta:ğ ol tavra:k akın akıtğa:n</b> translated ‘this mountain is quick at making the rain run (move) away’ (<i>sarī''u''l-isāla li''l-maṭar</i>) <i>I</i> 156: <i>KB</i> <b>akıtsa suvuğ yérde</b> ‘if you pour water on the ground’ 973; (we must open a vein and) <b>akıtğu kanı</b> ‘bleed him’ 1058; a.o. 1160 (<b>akın</b>): xıı(?) <i>KBVP</i> <b>xazīna tolulap akıtğu kerek</b> ‘you must fill (your) treasury and pour it out’ 51: xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>akıt-</b> ‘to pour out’ 47: <b>Xwar.</b> xıv ditto <i>Qutb</i> 10; <i>Nahc.</i> 68, 17.', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oğat-', 'oğat-', 'awaken, make recite', 'PU?S <b>oğat-</b> n.o.a.b.; in Syriac script, so the -ğ- is certain. In Muséon XXXVIII, p. 45 Bang equated this word with SE Tar. <b>oxat-</b>‘to awaken’ R <i>I</i> 1004, but that is unlikely since the original form of the latter, <b>*odğat-</b>, could hardly have lost the -d- so early. It is more likely that it is a Sec. f. of <b>okıt</b> or <b>ukıt-</b>, <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>oğatıp kelmiş bizni teg tınlığ-larka evangelyon nom ertinig nomlap kottuŋuz</b> ‘having come to make people like us recite (or ‘understand’) it(?) you have exhaustively taught the precious doctrine of the gospel’ <i>TT III</i> 62-3: <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. (you will certainly be reborn) <b>oğatmatın</b> [<b>séş?</b>]<b>metin</b> ‘without invoking(?) or . . .’ (the Buddhas) Suv. 24, 20.', 'Basic', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okıt-', 'okıt-', 'make recite, make read', 'D <b>okıt-</b> Caus. f. of <b>okı:-</b>; ‘to make (someone Acc. or Dat.) recite or read (something Acc.)’. s.i.a.m.l.g. usually as <b>okut-</b> and meaning ‘to teach’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>kim kayu tınlığ bu nom bitigig . . . okısar okıtsar</b> ‘whoever recites this scripture or has it recited’ <i>TT VI</i> 51-2; o.o. do. 68 (<i>TT VIII</i> O.9); <i>TT VII</i> 12, 10; 28, 3; Suv. 478, 19: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol maŋa: bitig okıttı:</b> ‘he made me read (<i>aqra''anī</i>) the book (etc.)’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 212 (<b>okıtur</b>, <b>okıtma:k</b>); <b>bu bitig ol kişi:ni: okıtğa:n</b> ‘this book, because of its length, makes a man read a lot’ (<i>kaṯīra(n) mā yuqri''</i>) <i>I</i> 156: <i>KB</i> (whoever was intelligent) <b>okıttı anı</b> ‘he had him summoned’ 416; (if a servant makes a mistake) <b>okıtğu kerek</b> ‘you must have him summoned’ 641: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>okut-</b> Caus. f.; <i>xwānāndan</i> ‘to cause to read, or recite’ <i>San.</i> 77v. 7: <b>Kom.</b> xıv ‘to teach’ <b>oğut-</b> <i>CCI</i>; <i>Gr.</i>: <b>Kıp.</b> xv <i>aqra''a</i> <b>okuç-</b> <i>Kav.</i> 69, 10; 75, 13; <i>istaqra''a</i> <b>okut-</b> <i>Tuh.</i> 54b. 8.', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ukıt-', 'ukıt-', 'explain', 'D <b>ukıt-</b> Caus. f. of <b>uk-</b>. N.o.a.b. Cf. <b>uktur-</b>. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. <b>öz tözlerin ukıttıp</b> ‘explaining their nature and origin’ <i>TT III</i> 30: Bud. <b>ukıtur</b> ‘he explains’ <i>TT VIII</i> A.16 and 17; o.o. do. A.30, H.1 and 2; these are the only texts in which <b>okıt-</b> and <b>ukıt-</b> are distinguished; it may have been misread elsewhere.', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okta:-', 'okta:-', 'load, cock, shoot', 'D <b>okta:-</b> Den. V. fr <b>1 ok</b>. Survives only in NE Khak., Tuv. and NC Kır., Kzx., usually ‘to load (a weapon); to cock (a rifle)’. The normal modern form is <b>okla-</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>keyik keligi: bolsa: okta:</b> <i>iḍā kāna waqt ḥuḍūri''l-waḥş fa''rmihi</i> ‘when the wild game comes, shoot it’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 26, 16: a.o. <i>II</i> 97, 16 (<b>utruş-</b>); n.m.e.', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oktat-', 'oktat-', 'order to shoot', 'D <b>oktat-</b> Hap. leg.; Caus. f. of <b>okta:-</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>beg anı: oktattı:</b> ‘the beg ordered him to shoot an arrow’ (<i>armāhu bi''l-nabl</i>) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 260 (<b>oktatur</b>, <b>oktatma:k</b>).', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağtıl-', 'ağtıl-', NULL, 'S <b>ağtıl-</b> See <b>ağtarıl-</b>.', 'Basic', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağtın-', 'ağtın-', 'mount, climb', 'D <b>ağtın-</b> Refl. f. of <b>ağıt-</b>. N.o.a.b. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. Sanskrit <i>yānam āruhya</i> ‘having mounted a chariot’ <b>kölökke: ağtınıp</b> <i>TT</i> <i>VIII</i> A.37; (in order that the flames of hell may not rise to meet me) <b>örtlüg yérlerde takı ağtınmazkan</b> ‘and in order that I may not be made to climb into fiery places’ U <i>II</i> 78, 42-3; a.o. Suv. 601, 23.', 'D', '[]', 81, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağtar-', 'ağtar-', 'turn over, roll over, translate', '<b>ağtar-</b>/<b>axtar-</b> apparently both Intrans. ‘to turn, or roll, over’ (rare) and Trans. ‘to turn, or roll, (something Acc.) over’, with some extended meanings like ‘to translate (a book etc. Acc.) from (one language Abl.) into (another -ça/-çe)’; more or less syn. with <b>evir-</b>, esp. in the last meaning. The second syllable, always -tar-, excludes the possibility that this is a Caus. f. Also partly syn. with <b>ağna:-</b>, but unlikely to be connected with it etymologically. As regards the velar, <i>Kaş.</i> is prob. right in saying that <b>ağtar-</b> was the original form, though he habitually uses <b>axtar-</b>, see his remarks on <b>sıgıt</b>; the <b>Uyğ.</b> script is too ambiguous to make the <b>Uyğ.</b> form certain. S.i.a.m.l.g., sometimes much distorted, e.g. NE <b>agdar-</b>/<b>agnar-</b>/<b>aŋar-</b>; NC, NW <b>awdar-</b> as well as more regular forms, <b>aktar-</b>/<b>axtar-</b> in the same groups. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>axtaru toŋdaru tegzinürler</b> ‘they revolve rolling about (Hend.)’ U <i>II</i> 4, 10 ff.; (Kitsi Samtso translated (<b>evirmiş</b>) this work from Indian into Chinese, and then Siŋku Salı Tutuŋ) <b>tavğaç tılıntın ikileyu türk tılınça axtarmış</b> ‘in the second place translated it from Chinese into Turkish’ U <i>I</i> 14, 5-7; similar phr. USp. 94, 8-9; Suv. 33, 19: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>er ta:şığ axtardı:</b> ‘the man turned over (<i>qallaba</i>) the stone’; and one says <b>tüpī: yığa:çığ axtardı:</b> ‘the gale knocked over (<i>asqaṭa</i>) the tree’; also used of anything that turns over (<i>qalaba</i>) anything; the -x- is altered from -ğ- as in Arabic <i>xaṭṭār</i>/ <i>ğaḍḍār</i> and <i>ximār</i>/<i>ğimār</i>; and one says <b>ol yé:r axtardı:</b> <i>''azaqa''l-arḍ wa karabahā</i>, ‘he dug the ground and turned it over’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 219 (<b>axtarur</b>, <b>axtarma:k</b>); <b>bastı: ölüm axtaru:</b> <i>şara''ahu''l-mawt</i> ‘death laid him low’ <i>I</i> 516, 4: same quotn. but <b>ağtaru:</b> <i>II</i> 74, 14: xıv <i>Muh.</i> <i>al-mayl</i> ‘to lean over’ <b>axtamak</b> (unvocalized, perhaps error for <b>axtarmak</b>) Mel. 37, 2; Rif. 122 (<i>māla</i> is translated <b>emit-</b>): <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>axtar-</b> <i>tafaḥḥuş kardan</i> ‘to examine, search (something)’ <i>San.</i> 32v. 8 (quotns.): <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>aktar-</b> <i>qalaba</i> <i>İd.</i> 17; <i>qalabajqallaba</i> <b>axtur-</b> (sic) <i>Bul.</i> 73v.: xv <i>qalaba</i> <b>aktar-</b> <i>Kav.</i> 74, 17; <i>Tuh.</i> 29b. 13: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>aktar-</b>/<b>axtar-</b>/<b>akdar-</b> (the last two rare) ‘to turn over, overthrow’ c.i.a.p. TTS <i>I</i> 15; <i>II</i> 21; <i>III</i> 11; <i>IV</i> 13.', 'Basic', '["axtar-"]', 81, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağtur-', 'ağtur-', 'lift, raise', 'D <b>ağtur-</b> Caus. f. of <b>1 a:ğ-</b>. Survives only(?) in SW <b>Osm.</b> <b>ağdır-</b>; <b>Tkm.</b> <b>a:ğdır-</b> with rather different meanings. Cf. <b>ağıt-</b>. <b>Türkü</b> vııı T 25 (<b>ığaç</b>): <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man.-A <b>xormuzda teŋrig tamudan yokaru ağturdı üntürdi</b> ‘he raised (Hend.) the God Hormuzd from hell’ <i>M I</i> 13, 18-20; <b>taŋda érte uluğ yaylıkka ağturmışın</b> ‘that he made (his disciples) go up to the summer room (i.e. lecture hall) early in the morning’ Hüen-ts. 1966-7: <b>Xak.</b> xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>ağdur-</b> ‘to raise’ 37: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>ağdur-</b> (later <b>ağdır-</b>) ‘to lift, raise’; c.i.a.p. TTS <i>I</i> 6; <i>II</i> 8; <i>III</i> 5; <i>IV</i> 5.', 'D', '[]', 82, 'DIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('aktur-', 'aktur-', 'pour out, cause to flow', 'D <b>aktur-</b> Caus. f. of <b>ak-</b>; ‘to pour out, cause to flow’. S.i.s.m.l., but rarer than <b>akıt-</b>. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Civ. [gap] <b>aktursar</b> ‘if one pours out . . .’ (on a Horse Day, it is unlucky) <i>TT VII</i> 39, 7: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol su:v akturdı:</b> <i>amara bi-tasyīli''l-mā'' wa isālatihi</i> ‘he ordered that the water should be poured out’; (verse) <b>akturur kö:züm yula:k</b> <i>tusil ''ayni ''uyūna''l-miyāh</i> ‘my eye pour out fountains of water’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 222 (<b>akturur</b>, <b>akturma:k</b>); same verse <i>III</i> 17, 9: xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>akdur-</b> ‘to pour out’ 47: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>aktur-</b>(-duŋ)/ <b>akız-</b>(-dı) <b>akıt-</b> <i>Vel.</i> 25 (quotn.); <b>akız-</b>/<b>aktur-</b> (spelt) Caus. f.; <i>rawān kardan</i> ‘to pour out’ <i>San.</i> 44v. 25 (quotn.): <b>Xwar.</b> xıv <b>aktur-</b> ditto <i>Qutb</i> 10; <i>Nahc.</i> 242, 14.', 'D', '[]', 82, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('uktur-', 'uktur-', 'make understand, explain', 'D <b>uktur-</b> Caus. f. of <b>uk-</b>; ‘to make (someone Dat.) understand (something Acc.); to explain (it to him)’. Survives in SE Türki: NC Kır. Cf. <b>ukıt-</b>. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>adınağuka biltürmedin ukturmadın</b> ‘without letting others know or understand’ <i>TT VI</i> 355 (v.l.); a.o. do. 147-8 (<b>ötgür-</b>): <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol maŋa: anıŋ sö:zin ukturdı:</b> ‘he explained to me (<i>afha-manī</i>) his words (etc.)’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 223 (<b>ukturur</b>, <b>ukturma:k</b>): <i>KB</i> <b>yayığ dunyā kılkın saŋa ukturur</b> ‘it explains the character of this fickle world to you’ 398; o.o. 510, 796, etc.: xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>uktur-</b> ‘to explain’ 325: xıv <i>Muh.</i>(?) <i>a''lama wa ''arrafa</i> ‘to communicate, make known’ <b>uktu:r-</b> Rif. 103; <i>''arrafa ğayrahu</i> <b>u:ktur-</b> 112 (only): <b>Xwar.</b> xıv <b>uktur-</b> ‘to explain’ <i>Qutb</i> 117 (<b>oktur-</b>): <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>ukțur-</b> <i>fahhama</i> <i>İd.</i> 17.', 'D', '[]', 82, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oktaş-', 'oktaş-', 'make a sudden movement, shy, compete in shooting', 'D <b>oktaş-</b> Recip. f. of <b>okta:-</b>. Survives only(?) in NC Kır. <b>oktos-</b> ‘to make a sudden movement, e.g. of a horse, to shy’. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol anıŋ birle: oktaştı:</b> translated <i>ramāhu bi''l-sahm</i> ‘he shot an arrow at him’ (error for <i>rāmāhu</i> ‘he competed in shooting’); also used for <i>qāra''ahu</i> ‘he drew lots with him’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 231 (<b>oktaşur</b>, <b>oktaşma:k</b>).', 'D', '[]', 82, 'DIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okıtçı:', 'okıtçı:', 'summoner', 'D <b>okıtçı:</b> Hap. leg.; possibly a scribal error for <b>okı:çı</b>, q.v.; if not, an abbreviation, metrī gratia, of <b>*okıdaçı:</b> N./A. fr. <b>okı:-</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <i>KB</i> <b>méni ıdtı él(l)ig okıtçı saŋa</b> ‘the king sent me to you to summon you’ 3488.', 'D', '[]', 82, 'TRIS. AGD');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağtarıl-', 'ağtarıl-', 'be overturned', 'D <b>ağtarıl-</b>/<b>axtarıl-</b> Pass. f. of <b>ağtar-</b>/<b>axtar-</b>survives in most of the same languages with the same phonetic changes. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <b>kemi axtarılur</b> ‘the ship is overturned’ PP 18, 3; <b>axtarılu toŋdarılu</b> ‘rolling over and over (Hend.)’ Suv. 133, 21; 601, 11-12: Civ. (the cold water which rises in the well) <b>axtarılu yanturu yorıdı</b> ‘has been turned over and goes back’ <i>TT I</i> 105: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>er ağtıldı:</b> ‘the man was knocked down’ (<i>şuri''a</i>); its original form was <b>ağtarıldı:</b> <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 246 (<b>ağtılur</b>, <b>ağtılma:k</b>): xıv <i>Muh.</i> <i>inqalaba</i> ‘to be overturned’ <b>axtarıl-</b> Mel. 20, 10; Rif. 104: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>axtarıl-</b> <i>tafaḥḥuş şudan</i> ‘to be searched’ <i>San.</i> 32v. 26: <b>Osm.</b> xıv, xv <b>axtarıl-</b>/<b>aktarıl-</b>/<b>akdarıl-</b> ‘to be overturned, turned away’ in several texts TTS <i>I</i> 15; <i>II</i> 19; <i>III</i> 11; <i>IV</i> 13.', 'D', '["axtarıl-"]', 82, 'TRIS. V. AĞD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okıtsa:-', 'okıtsa:-', 'wish to have read', 'D <b>okıtsa:-</b> Hap. leg.; Desid. f. of <b>okıt-</b>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ol bitig okıtsa:dı:</b> ‘he wished to have the book read’ (<i>yuqri''a''l-kitāb</i>); also used of wishing to summon (<i>yad''ū</i>) someone <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 302 (<b>okıtsa:r</b>, <b>okıtsa:ma:k</b>).', 'D', '[]', 82, 'TRIS. V. AGD-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('akığ', 'akığ', 'flow, flowing, liquid', 'D <b>akığ</b> Dev. N./A.Ac. fr. <b>ak-</b>; ‘flow, flowing; liquid’. Survives as <b>ağığ</b> in NE Leb., Şor R <i>I</i> 154 and <b>ağu:</b> in NE Alt., Tel.; NC Kzx.; NW Kaz. R <i>I</i> 172. Similar forms with final -k in some languages seem rather to represent Ar. <i>''aqīq</i> ‘a ravine worn by a stream’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. (in a list of demons who are foul feeders, between those that eat <b>yiriŋ</b> ‘pus’ and those that eat <b>söl</b> ‘moisture, juice’, <b>yar</b> ‘spittle’, and <b>léşip</b> ‘mucus’) <b>akığ aşlığlar</b> ‘eaters of serum’(?) U <i>II</i> 65, 19; 66, 42; in technical Buddhist terminology <b>akığ</b> (more particularly in its der. f.s <b>akığlığ</b>, <b>akığsız</b>) translates Sanskrit <i>srava</i> (Chinese lou, Giles 7,360) lit. ‘flowing’, metaph. ‘restlessness, impermanence’ <i>TT VI</i>, note 157-61; (mortals) <b>alku akığların alkıp</b> ‘suppressing all their restlessnesses’ Suv. 185, 20-1; <b>az ulati nızvanılarığ akığlarığ</b> ‘the passions and restlessnesses, lust and so on’ U <i>III</i> 88, 4-5: Civ. [gap] <b>a:kağ yolla:rda:</b> ‘in the (internal) vessels (that carry) liquids’ <i>TT VIII</i> I.7 (prob. the gullet, intestines, etc., not the veins).', 'D', '[]', 82, 'DIS. AGĞ');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oxa:k', 'oxa:k', 'juice of split apricots', 'VU?F <b>oxa:k</b> Hap. leg.; prob. an Iranian(?) l.-w. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>oxa:k</b> <i>‘uşāra falīqi''l-mişmiş yuşrab</i> ‘the juice of split apricots’, used as a beverage <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 122.', 'VU', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AG');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('okığ', 'okığ', 'questionnaire', 'D <b>okığ</b> Dev. N. fr. <b>okı:-</b>. Survives, usually as <b>oku:</b> and the like in NC <b>Kır.</b>, <b>Kzx.</b>, and some NW and SW languages. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Civ. emdi bu künde kén bu korçularka <b>okığlar</b> ayıtlar ıdmazun <i>USp.</i> 45, 8-9; this document is confused and largely unintelligible; <b>korçu</b> here is prob. a Mong. l.-w., lit. ‘bowman’, a kind of minor official (Haenisch 67); <b>ayıtlar</b> Hap. leg. if correctly read, should mean ‘questionnaire’; ‘now from this day onwards he must not send summonses and questionnaires to these <b>korçus</b>’.', 'D', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AGĞ');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('uğuk', 'uğuk', 'felt gaiters or leggings', '<b>uğuk</b> some form of leg-wear, prob. ‘felt gaiters or leggings’. The contracted form noted by <i>San.</i> survives as <b>uk</b> ‘felt stocking’ in all NE dialects. There is another Sec. f. <b>uyuk</b> in NC <b>Kzx.</b>: NW Kaz. R <i>I</i> 1318 (only): SW xx Anat. (refugees) SDD 1424. The entry in <b>Uyğ.</b> xıv <i>Chin.-Uyğ. Dict.</i> <i>wa</i> ‘felt stockings’ (Giles 12,434) <b>uçuk</b> R <i>I</i> 1735; Ligeti 273 can hardly be an error for this work. <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>uğuk</b> <i>al-curmūq</i> ‘gaiters, leggings’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 67: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>uğ</b> . . . (2) <i>mūza ki az pūst-i paşmdār bā-dūzand</i> ‘boots made of leather with the wool on it’ <i>San.</i> 76v. 18.', 'Basic', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AĞG');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ukuğ', 'ukuğ', 'understanding', 'D <b>ukuğ</b> N.Ac. fr. <b>uk-</b>; ‘understanding’. Survives only(?) in NC <b>Kır.</b> <b>uğu:</b> Cf. <b>ukuş</b>, which is the normal word in <i>KB</i>. <b>Xak.</b> xı <i>KB</i> aŋar bérdi erdem bilig ög <b>ukuğ</b> ‘(God) gave him (i.e. man) manly virtues, knowledge, intelligence, and understanding’ 148.', 'D', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AGĞ');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağuk-', 'ağuk-', 'be poisoned', 'D <b>ağuk-</b> Pass. Den. V. fr. <b>ağu:</b>. Survives only(?) in NE Khak. <b>o:x-</b>; Tuv. <b>o:k-</b> ‘to be poisoned’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Man. az nızvanıka <b>ağukup</b> ‘being poisoned by the passion of lust’ <i>TT III</i> 28: Bud. yélvikip <b>ağukup</b> öltürgeli sakınsar ‘if he plans to kill him by sorcery or poison’ <i>Kuan.</i> 184; öḏsüz ölüm yélvikmek <b>ağukmak</b> ‘to die prematurely by sorcery or poison’ <i>Suv.</i> 472, 15; o.o. (without <b>yélvik-</b>) <i>Suv.</i> 593, 17; <i>USp.</i> 102a. 7: <b>Xak.</b> xı er <b>ağuktı:</b> ‘the man was poisoned’ (summa); this is Pass. (lāzim) <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 191 (<b>ağuka:r</b>, <b>ağukma:k</b>): <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>ağuk-</b><i>masmūm şudan</i> ‘to be poisoned’ <i>San.</i> 43v. 10.', 'D', '[]', 83, 'DIS. V. AĞG-');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('akığlığ', 'akığlığ', 'impermanent, restless', 'D <b>akığlığ</b> P.N./A. fr. <b>akığ</b> in its technical Bud. sense; translates Sanskrit <i>sāsrava</i> ‘impermanent, restless’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <i>TT VI</i>, note 157-61, several examples; <i>Suv.</i> 354, 5 (<b>oxşatığsız</b>).', 'D', '[]', 83, 'TRIS. AGĞ');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('akığsız', 'akığsız', 'stable, permanent, not restless', 'D <b>akığsız</b> Priv. N./A. fr. <b>akığ</b> in its technical Bud. sense; translates Sanskrit <i>anāsrava</i> ‘stable, permanent, not restless’. <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı ff. Bud. <i>TT VI</i>, note 157-61, several examples.', 'D', '[]', 83, 'TRIS. AGĞ');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('ağıl', 'ağıl', 'enclosure, cattle-pen, sheep-fold, settlement', '<b>ağıl</b> originally ‘an enclosure for livestock; cattle-pen, sheep-fold’; thence ‘a settlement or group of tents’ associated with such an enclosure. An early, ?First Period, l.-w. in Mong. as <i>ayil</i> (Haenisch 11, Kow. 3), and in Russian (fr. a NW language) as <i>aul</i>. Survives as <b>ağıl</b> in SE <b>Türki</b>, Shaw 11; SC Uzb. (<b>oğıl</b>) and SW <b>Az.</b> <b>Osm.</b>, <b>Tkm.</b> (<b>a:ğıl</b>) and as <b>awl</b> in some NC and NW languages. The form <b>ayıl</b> in some NE and NC languages is a reborrowing fr. Mong. See Doerfer <i>II</i> 503. <b>Türkü</b> vııı ff. <b>ağılıŋta: yilkı:ŋ bolzu:n</b> ‘may you get livestock in your pens’ <i>IrkB</i> 47: <b>Uyğ.</b> ıx (I was a rich man) <b>ağılım on yılkım sansız erti:</b> ‘I had ten pens and innumerable livestock’ <i>Suci</i> 5: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>ağıl</b> <i>marbaḍu''l-ğanam</i> ‘sheepfold’; and in <b>Oğuz</b> <i>rawṭu''l-ğanam</i> ‘sheep’s dung’, because the two are closely connected, just as in Ar. both ‘rain’ and ‘clouds’ are called <i>samā</i> <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 73: <b>ağı:lda:</b> (sic) <b>oğla:k tuğsa:</b> ‘if a kid is born in the fold’ <i>I</i> 65, 21: xııı(?) <i>Tef.</i> <b>ağıl</b> ‘sheep-fold’ 37: xıv <i>Muh.(?) marbaḍu''l-ğanam</i> <b>ağıl</b> <i>Rif.</i> 179 (only): <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>ağıl</b> (1) <i>hāla-i māh</i> ‘a halo round the moon’; (2) <i>muḥawwaṭa</i> ‘enclosure’, which they make for cattle to sleep in; also used in Pe. <i>San.</i> 76v. 18; <b>awul</b> (spelt) ‘a place in which nomadic tribes (<i>īlāt</i>) collect and settle down’; a corruption of Ar. <i>ḥawīlī</i> ‘a small enclosure, yard’ <i>San.</i> 53v. 7 (no doubt an xvııı, not a <b>Çağ.</b> word, the etymology is absurd): <b>Oğuz</b> xı see <b>Xak.</b>: <b>Kıp.</b> xıv <b>ağıl</b> <i>al-ḥaẓīra</i> ‘enclosure’; <i>ḥaẓīratu''l-ğanam</i> <b>ko:yun ağlı:</b> (sic) <i>İd.</i> 16: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>ağıl</b>/<b>ağul</b> ‘sheep-fold’ in xıv <i>TTS I</i> 6, 13; ‘halo’ in all periods in <b>ay ağılı</b> <i>I</i> 55; <i>II</i> 72; <i>III</i> 5, 49; <i>IV</i> 6, 51, 373 (<b>gün ağılı</b>).', 'Basic', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AĞL');
INSERT INTO words (word, normalized_word, meaning, full_entry_text, etymology_type, variants, page, skeleton) VALUES ('oğul', 'oğul', 'offspring, child, son', '<b>oğul</b> ‘offspring, child’, originally of either sex, but with a strong implication of ‘male child’; by itself it can mean ‘son’, but not ‘daughter’; in the Plur. it might mean ‘sons and daughters’, but <b>oğul kız</b> would be the more normal expression. One of the very few Turkish words forming a Plur. in <b>-n</b>. Thus <b>oğla:n</b> was originally the Plur. and understood as such, but this fact was later forgotten and <b>oğul</b> came to mean ‘son’, and <b>oğla:n</b> ‘boy’ and later ‘servant’ or ‘bodyguard’ (the origin of German Uhlan); the timing of these changes has not yet been worked out. Both words s.i.a.m.l. with various phonetic changes. See Doerfer <i>II</i> 498, 502. <b>Türkü</b> vııı various suffixed forms <b>oğlım</b>, <b>oğlı:</b>, etc. are common in <i>I</i>, <i>II</i>, <i>T</i>, etc.; <b>oğlanım</b>, clearly Plur., <i>I S</i> 1, <i>II N</i> 1; <i>I N</i> 11; <b>oğlanıŋızda:</b> Plur. <i>I SE</i>; a.o. <i>I E</i> 5, <i>II E</i> 5 (<b>atı:</b>); vııı ff. <b>oğlı:</b> <i>IrkB</i> 15, etc.; (a gambler staked) <b>oğlanı:n kisi:si:n</b> ‘his sons (or children) and his wife’ do. 29; <b>oğlanım ınça: bili:ŋler</b> ‘my sons, know this’ do. Postscript: Yen. <b>oğlı:</b> <i>Mal.</i> 30, 2 etc.; <b>sü teŋi: yeti: biŋ oğlan erti:</b> do. 26, 8 must mean ‘the strength of the army was 7,000 young men’ (sic, not ‘sons’); <b>on ay éltdi: ögüm oğlan tuğdım</b> ‘I was born a boy (not Plur.) whom his mother had carried for ten months’ do. 29, 5: Man. <b>Xormuzta teŋri oğlanı béş teŋri</b> ‘the five gods, the sons (Plur.) of the god Hormuzd’ <i>Chuas.</i> <i>I</i> 8; a.o. do. 33: <b>Uyğ.</b> vııı <b>eki: oğlıma:</b> ‘to my two sons’ <i>Şu. E</i> 7: ıx <b>oğlanım</b> ‘oh my sons’ <i>Suci</i> 9 (<b>oğlımın</b> in do. 6 is a misreading of <b>bağladım</b>) vııı ff. Man.-A kaltı <b>oğul</b> <b>oğlan</b> ergüsinte erürçe ‘just as a child comes to maturity (2 <b>ér-</b>) in the womb’ (lit. ‘place for children’) <i>M I</i> 14, 12-14; (and the magicians) <b>oğul kız bérü umağaylar</b> ‘will not be able to give him sons and daughters’ do. 15, 10: Man. alku tınlığ <b>oğlanınıŋ</b> ‘of all the children of men’ <i>TT III</i> 19: Chr. amrak <b>oğlanlarım</b> (sic) ‘my dear sons’ <i>U I</i> 5, 4: <b>teŋri oğlı</b> ‘the son of God’ do. 7, 1; <b>oğlan kızlar</b> ‘boys and girls’ (below the age of two) do. 10, 2: Bud. <b>oğul</b>, <b>oğlı</b>, etc. ‘boy, son’ are common <i>TT VII</i>, <i>VIII</i>; <i>PP</i> 11, 6 etc.; tınlığ <b>oğlanıŋa</b> <i>TT VII</i> 40, 142; in <i>TT V</i> 12, 127 (a fairly late text) <b>teŋridem kız azu teŋri oğlanı teg körkle oğlan</b> ‘a child as beautiful as a divine girl or a son of God’ <b>oğlan</b> is clearly Sing.: Civ. <b>oğluŋ kisiŋ ülüglüg ol</b> ‘your children and wives are fortunate’ <i>TT I</i> 154-5; <b>kişi oğlı ög(k)e kelmez</b> ‘children do not come to their mother’ do. 216; <b>kiçiğ oğlan</b> ‘a small boy (Sing.)’ do. 161; <i>TT VII</i> 27, 8; <b>kenç oğlan</b> ‘a young boy’ <i>TT VII</i> 23, 2; <i>H II</i> 12, 87: xıv <b>Uyğ.-Chin. Dict.</b> ‘son, boy’ <b>oğul</b> Ligeti 186: <b>O. Kır.</b> ıx ff. <b>oğlım</b>, <b>oğlı</b> are common; <b>oğlanım</b> <i>Mal.</i> 1, 1 etc. is clearly Plur. but <b>oğlan atım</b> do. 45, 1 seems to mean ‘my name as a boy’: <b>Xak.</b> xı <b>oğul</b> <i>al-ibn</i> ‘son’; and <i>ğayru''l-ibn mina''l-şibyān</i> ‘boys who are not (a man’s) sons’ are called <b>oğul</b>; hence one says bu <b>oğul</b> ne: té:r ‘what does this boy (<i>al-şabī</i>) say?’; <i>wa yucma'' . . . ''alā ğayri''l-qiyās</i> and it forms the irregular Plur. <b>oğla:n</b> but <b>oğulla:r</b> is also permissible as Plur.; this is like the word <b>eren</b> for <i>al-ricāl</i> ‘men’; <i>wa qad yuwahhad kilāhumā</i>, and both of them are used in the Sing. <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 74; about 70 o.o. of <b>oğul</b> and 50 of <b>oğla:n</b>: <i>KB</i> <b>oğul</b> normally ‘son’ is common, 110, 186, 187, etc.; <b>kiçig oğlanığ</b> ‘a small boy’ 293, 1097, etc.; <b>atın tutti mindi bir oğlan bile</b> ‘he took his horse and rode off with one page’ 4970: xııı(?) <i>At.</i> <b>Maḥmūd oğlı</b> 496; <i>Tef.</i> <b>oğul</b> ‘son’, Plur. <b>oğullar</b>; <b>oğlan</b> ‘child, boy’; also? Collective Plur. 231: xıv <i>Muh.</i> <i>al-nasl wa''l-ḍuriya</i> ‘offspring’ <b>o:ğul</b> <i>Rif.</i> 143; <i>al-şabī</i> <b>oğla:n</b> 85: <b>Çağ.</b> xv ff. <b>oğul</b> <i>farzand</i> ‘son’ <i>San.</i> 77r. 6; <b>oğlan</b> (spelt) <i>pisar wa farzand</i> ‘boy, son’; and metaph. ‘beardless boy’; and they call the sons of the Mongol Xans <b>oğlan</b> just as Persian princes are called <i>mirzā</i> and Rūmī princes <i>sulṭān</i>; <b>oğlan aşı</b> <i>cundbidastar</i> ‘castoreum’, beaver’s glands, called in Turkish <b>kunduz</b> do. 76v. 24: <b>Arğu</b> xı <b>oğla:</b> (sic) <i>al-fatā</i> ‘youth’ <i>Kaş.</i> <i>I</i> 129: <b>Xwar.</b> xııı(?) <b>oğul</b> ‘son’; Plur. <b>oğullar</b> common in Oğ.: xıv <b>oğlan</b> ‘boy’ <i>Qutb</i> 114; <b>oğul</b> ‘son’ <i>MN</i> 15: <b>Kom.</b> xıv ‘son’ <b>oğul</b> <i>CCI</i>; <b>oğul</b>/<b>ovul</b> Plur. <b>oğlanlar</b> <i>CCG</i>; <i>Gr.</i> 173 (many suffixed forms): <b>Kıp.</b> xııı <i>al-şabī</i> <b>owla:n</b> also called <b>oğla:n</b>; <i>al-ṭifl</i> ‘child’ <b>kenç oğla:n</b>; <i>al-raḍī</i> ‘foster child’ <b>ağuz oğla:n</b> <i>Hou.</i> 24, 20; <i>al-walad</i> ‘son’ <b>oğul</b> do. 32, 2: xıv <b>oğul</b> <i>al-ibn</i>, in Kıpçak (sic) <b>owul</b> <i>İd.</i> 16; <b>oğla:n</b> <i>al-ğulām</i> ‘boy, page’ do. 16; <i>al-ibn</i> <b>oğlan</b>/<b>oğul</b> <i>Bul.</i> 9. 2: xv <b>oğlum</b> <i>ibni</i> <i>Kav.</i> 15, 20; <b>oğlı:</b> do. 44, 12; 59, 12; <i>walad</i> <b>owul</b>, in <b>Tkm.</b> <b>oğul</b> <i>Tuh.</i> 38a. 8; <i>al-şabī</i> <b>olan</b> and (<b>Tkm.</b>) <b>oğlan</b> do. 78b. 6: <b>Osm.</b> xıv ff. <b>oğul</b> ‘son’, mainly in phr. <i>TTS I</i> 536; <i>III</i> 535; <i>IV</i> 601; <b>oğlan</b> ‘son; child (male or female)’ by itself and in phr. <i>II</i> 717 ff.; <i>III</i> 533 ff.; <i>IV</i> 599 ff.; xvııı <b>oğul otı</b> in Rūmī, <i>bādrancbūya</i> ‘mountain balm’ <i>San.</i> 77r. 6.', 'Basic', '[]', 83, 'DIS. AĞL');
